I learned something about 10 years ago. I took part in a massive, international talent project which ended in tears for me, and many others involved. Yet years on I regularly treasure fond memories from that season. The experience taught me something profound... There will be wounds, disappointments and trials in every season. But in EVERY season there is gold, and that gold... Will be found in the people who surround you. The cast of each life-scene never truly exits the stage of your heart. Gold is hidden in shared moments of understanding and compassion - glittering and glowing in knowing nods and loaded hugs. It lingers in timely advice, like delicious apples of truth. My advice to everyone in 2023 is, get ready to soak up all your people moments, however varied. Even the confrontations and disagreements conceal hidden treasure. Get ready to glean the honey of wisdom, drink the dew of growth from all that beautiful, raw, humanity. Doors open and close. Seasons change. The leaves of your normal fall to the ground and return to the soil. But the mileage you do with other souls, moving together towards the light is eternal. You will recall it to the end of your days. You'll share it with your children. You'll build your world around it. And ultimately, by God's grace you'll take it to the next world with you. May God bless your relationships, your interactions and your interpersonal journeys this coming year in Jesus name. Everything else is as temporary as Christmas tinsel ☺️❤️🎄❤️☺️🎄

'WHAT AM I DOING WITH MY LIFE?'...It is a common New Year's question. Whilst we look to the future, we can also find ourselves ruminating about what we've achieved (or not) over the past year. We can find ourselves comparing ourselves to the overachievers gallery of Instagram, wondering why we're not Billionaire entrepreneurs or the perfect example of an influencer, artist or nuclear family. Worse still, we can compare ourselves to who we were during a more fruitful or exciting season in life. Let me take a load off your shoulders ...

Firstly, you've survived a pandemic and the subsequent, ropey reintroduction to 'normality'. You've likely survived illness and weathered grief in the past year. You're surviving a major cost of living crisis. And above all of that.. God created you for good WORKS, plural, not WORK singular. You don't have a single function or purpose. As the seasons come and go, your purpose evolves & adapts. Your value never changes. The world would have you believe you're on a linear, one-way journey to a specific outcome, gradually working your way to success, waiting for the day you 'arrive' as the best you. That's not what God says... 

 ✨Your life isn't over - there's still time to create and reach new and beautiful goals. Write something down and pray over it! Ask God to help you get there. 

✨Your work is ALWAYS to believe. Have faith for your needs in the here and now, and walk the journey together with God. This is a purpose in itself.

✨Your job is to love others. Someone needs you right now. If you're serving them in love, you're on fire with purpose today. 

Don't believe the insta-lies. You're amazing, worthy and doing so much better than you think. 🙏❤️🙏❤️🙏 HAPPY NEW YEAR
HAPPY NEW YEEEEEEEEEAR. COME ON 2023✨

Why we don't pursue our dreams...

It's not because we're incapable 
It's not because we lack talent 
It's not necessarily that we lack the discipline or the drive
It's not even because we're afraid 

I honestly believe we avoid pursuing our dreams because deep down, on a cellular level we don't actually believe we deserve them. We see others winning, thriving, starting businesses reaching goals and we think of them as the chosen ones. We don't put ourselves in the picture. 

I want to empower you for 2023... This is the year to put yourself in the picture. This is the year to play the lead in the movie of your own life. I believe that God imprints dreams within us. If we can dream it, we can reach for it! 

Why not you? Why shouldn't you be the trailblazer? Why shouldn't you burst through the finishline tape? Maybe it's time for you to create something beautiful. Maybe it's your year to renovate a property or start a business. Maybe it's your year to introduce change in your workplace or school. Maybe it's time to present the work of your heart to the world. Why...not...you? Guys, just give it a go for God this year. Whatever happens you can look back and say 2023 was the year I stopped thinking the victory moments and blessings were only for 'others'.

Today I went to the cinema alone. I'm away on work so I thought, 'Hey why not? A little 'me-time' might go a long way. So I ate in the restaurant by myself (stared at my phone the whole time, it was great), then took myself to see the Whitney movie. Boy did that hit hard. The most decorated female singer in history, taken advantage of and led astray by those closest in her life. Consumed by the pressure of meeting public and personal expectations. So highly valued as an artist yet in so many ways, undervalued as a regular, beautiful person. 

Hearing Whitney's heavenly voice singing those words, 'Learning to love yourself is the greatest love of all.' unlocked a flood of emotion for me, because it was the very first song I properly learned, (I was just a little older than Ozma at the time). I started to think about the many roles we play as people and how easy it is to lose ourselves. 

So here are some thoughts that might keep you from getting lost altogether...

 - Don't get so caught up taking care of others that you forget to take care of yourself. This is not a bath salts commercial, it can be the difference between a life well-lived and a life cut short.

 - Have a long hard think about what success is to you. 'Success' is meaningless if it compromises your soul on any level. For me success is my daughter's smile. End of.

 - Don't mistake adulation for actual love. Love builds you. Adulation will consume you if you allow it.

 - People are good at making all sorts of plans for your life. If you don't make your own and guard them you'll end up living out someone else's. (God's plan is a whole other TED talk. You know what I'm getting at).

- Maybe you're justifiably asking yourself, 'Who is looking out for me right now? Who is making sure I'm ok?' The Holy Spirit says, 'How about you? Are YOU making sure you're ok? Are you saying no when you need to? Are you telling the truth about how you feel? Others will treat you with the measure of kindness you use for yourself.'

 - Finally don't take it for granted that others will look out for your best interests even if they claim to care for you. You may come across that sort of altruism occasionally, but it's 👇

I know what it's like to be rejected. I know what it's like to seem 'odd' to others, to have them make fun of or exclude you. I know what it's like to feel like no one really wants you around, or like the scapegoat in social situations. I know what it's like to make social mistakes and become a joke in the corridors at school. And even though I've created a career for myself where people say nice things to me and listen when I talk, a little part of me will always feel like the youngest in the family, the creative quirky one who makes themselves a target by saying the wrong thing. I know the pain of that. Sometimes I wonder if most of my efforts in life are some elaborate attempt to give that kid a hug 😆 Whoa, that's deep 😳. This is not a pity party, I just had it in my heart to tell you this...

I wouldn't change a thing. My quirkiness was always God's design and it has become my creative superpower. My way of looking at the world is valuable and refreshing to others I know that now. And I've learned how to present myself in a way that makes sense to the world, but makes sense to me too (mostly). I have found love and friendships, real ones. I have found a career that suits my strengths. In many ways I've been fashioned by God from a bendy little sapling into an arrow - made to fly. 

I just wanted to tell you this, because if you're like me, sometimes still struggling to find your social spot, masking your awkwardness with humour and often feeling at a loss when connecting with others, you're not alone. In fact you're in good company. You may sometimes feel lonely, but please don't interpret that as unwanted or worthless. ☺️🙏 God made everything beautiful in its time, including you. You may sometimes feel like a fish on a bicycle, but we all have genius in the right lab ☺️ Stay you, friend.

Imagine having your first Nashville Waffle House experience... And besides the good old fashioned coffee and comfort food, meeting someone rather special. This is quite the Southern fairytale truth be told. A sweet lady sat eating brunch alone on the next table to us. She smiled kindly as my friends and I sang along with the duke box. We'd playlisted some of our faves, classics like 'Goodbye Yellow Brick road' and 'Dont stop believing' by Journey. Ozma ate her fill of hash browns and scrambled egg, and as we wound up breakfast our dear friend Russ kindly offered to pick up our tab. Being the top-drawer gentleman he is, he also offered to bless the sweet lady who was eating alone. They began chatting and before long the conversation extended across to our table. Russ told Joel that this ladies' late husband was a drummer. Boy was he a drummer...

Turns out this lady is Debbie Londin. Her late husband Larrie Londin was in one of the first ever bands to be signed by Motown Records. He played with everyone from Marvin Gaye and  Stevie Wonder to Diana Ross and the Temptations. In 1969 Chet Atkins (gasp) convinced him to quit the band and move to Nashville. It was a good move. He spent his career playing for the biggest stars in pop and country including Dolly Parton and the late Elvis Presley. He played on a number of iconic records too including 'Jolene' and yes... 'Dont stop believing' by Journey. She joked that she appreciates the Duke Box spins as she still collects the royalties 🙏😆

She wished us well and complimented my singing. It was the most wonderful meet-cute, made possible only by the Southern kindness of Russ Williams. What a rich and beautiful blessing I sure won't forget. Thank you Russ. Thank you Jesus. Thank you Nashville 
#OnlyInNashville

It's my birthday 🎉 And unfortunately I've spent the last 2 days in bed with a chest infection which thankfully seems to be improving with antibiotics. But I'm reflecting on what I've learned this year of my life...

1) I'm hecka stronger than I ever imagined. I've overcome a truck load of adversity/anxiety to get back on stage and into my lane. Honestly, I can't convey the half of it. I CAN DO HARD THINGS. 

2) I love Jesus and I believe God can do the miraculous/the impossible etc. But sometimes He doesn't. And that's ok, because he's already done enough by being the Messiah. He doesn't owe me anything.

3) Working hard is great, but striving is futile. There's no need. Nothing I say, do, no song I write or sing will make me more visible to Him. We're good. I just need to enter His incredible rest. 

4) I have no interest in manipulating anyone or their ideas about me. For a long time I had an illusion that if I presented myself in a certain way it would gain favour, attention or success. I really don't wanna work for anyone's approval these days. I just wanna do what I love, be a light wherever I go, be a loving friend and family member. The right doors will always open.

Love you guys and thanks for being with me on the journey xx

I love great worship music. I love awesome musicians who use their talents for Jesus and bring the house down on a Sunday.  But I also love that we don't need an army of talented people to pull back the veil and lead us into the throne room. We don't actually need a minister's permission or supervision to enter into God's presence. As believers we can be with God any time, anywhere, because the veil has been torn by Jesus. He is our VIP pass. He's our entry into heaven! Isn't that AWESOME!?

So yes, we can love Bethel, Maverick, whoever and all that they bring. We can enjoy the inspiration and the freshness these beautiful ministers bring. But equally, Jesus is enough. We can be surrounded by the glory in our living rooms. We can be drenched in his presence as we drive to the shops, or mow the lawn. Isn't that awesome? More to the point - he is here. Right now. No bells or whistles required. 
Wow. Praise our generous, present God 👍💕

In the valley of shadows it's hard to see what's ahead. I want to encourage you today - if you're struggling, ask the Holy spirit to take your hard and lead you one small step at a time. 

I can assure you, God is faithful. I can't believe the storms he has walked me through in recent years. When the low mood wouldn't shift after Ozma was born and the tiniest of tasks filled me with terror, God remained with me. He whispered to me in the depths of my fear, coaching me through each small step forward. He gave me little breadcrumbs, manna from heaven to guide me out of darkness. When I could barely function he would speak to my spirit, 'Get dressed. Open the window. Walk and breathe in the air. Sit outside with Ozma when it's bright. Bare with the noise in your mind, it will settle. See a friend. It's ok if you're not the life and soul of the party, you'll dance again. Go to Church. Sit at the back if that's all you can do. Say yes to work opportunities. I know you're anxious but I'll be there. You can do it. And you can be a mum. You do have it in you because I put it there.' Honestly, these are the things I've felt in my spirit as God led me through the wilderness, and brought me out into a spacious place. 

If you're struggling right now, lean into Jesus. If you're in the shadows, struggling to imagine or believe in the bigger picture of God's plan, just trust the gentle voice of the Holy spirit to give you a pixel at a time. Just a dot, a corner. Let Him lead and trust.

IF SCROLLING IS MAKING YOU FEEL RUBBISH...

Just remember, this is where the majority of people come to share their good news and celebrate their wins. In reality, for every 'win' there are a dozen losses. For every glam photo, there are a stack of bad skin days, greasy hair days and grubby old tracksuit bottom moments. Behind every well-shod wedding anniversary is a journey of highs and mega lows. There's a catalogue of make-or-break conversations about where the heck we're going and what the heck we're doing. There are toddler tantrums and teenage rebellions. There are weak and pathetic pity parties, low moods and struggles with sin. You betcha. 

So... Should we stop sharing the good stuff? No way. The truly good moments are worth marking with flowers and bunting. Should we tell everyone our secrets then? Even LESS way 😆 Share a dose of reality now and again so we can remember we're not alone? Yes please. And just remember, Facebook isn't anyone's proper front room. It's more of a high end kitchen showroom where the sink isn't really plumbed in and the sky is painted into the windows.

We even wrap our lows in virtuous sentiment on socials, giving the darkest times an attractive veneer. I think it's worth noting, real life is quite unattractive and unremarkable most of the time. So. Rest easy in your boringness this afternoon. Feel free to sit in your real life and be thoroughly unimpressed with yourself. It's ok. 

And it doesn't make you ungrateful to do so. In fact, it might inspire you to be more grateful, because there is plenty of value, beauty and meaning to be found outside of awards, milestones and mountain top moments.

⭐ Right now, the enemy may be having a field day with your thought life ⭐.

Here are a few stray thoughts that I've identified as being from the enemy (or at least thoughts that the enemy delights in):

- You randomly get mad at someone for offenses you've already chosen to forgive.

- You imagine every possible way a trustworthy person could betray you.

- You dwell on all the ways people have let you down or disappointed you.

- You mentally list all your flaws and failings.

- You catastrophize your future.

- You blame yourself for everything wrong in your world.

- You overanalyze your past and formulate theories about what might be wrong with you (and what wrongs you've committed).

- You script imaginary conversations about others rejecting or gossiping about you.

These are just a few examples of the kinds of thoughts that lead to discouragement, distrust, and depression. When such thoughts guide our words, actions, or decisions, they're destructive. They breed decay in our lives where God intends for life to bloom. They may seem protective, but they're like rotten cabbages stuffed in our pockets - heavy and unpleasant.

Our bodies or brains may generate these thoughts as a response to trauma or abuse, but God doesn't want us to carry these trauma responses into our tomorrow. His mercies are new every day, and He intends for our emotions and thoughts to be healthy, enabling us to live our best lives.

We need to let scripture serve as the light by which we examine our thoughts, determining whether they're worthless or valuable.If you're struggling with this, start by observing your thoughts as they come.

See them as passersby with uninformed opinions. Mentally close the window and silence them if they're not helpful. Believe me, if they make you feel powerless, unlovable, worthless, bitter, or hopeless, they're not helpful! They're not in line with God's will for your mind.

Here's why: God has chosen YOU as the light of this generation. No matter how flawed and imperfect you and your journey may be, you are His workmanship created for good works. Let's stand firm in this conviction for the rest of 2023.

I had the sweetest time with my little crew in Copenhagen this weekend! Our visit was short and sweet, playing at a small church garden party. This one was a bit different though, overlooked by a high-rise block of apartments. Dozens, maybe even hundreds, of households leaned over their balconies to listen in. Children spilled onto the terrace, curiously absorbing the sound of our tunes. It felt so wholesome. Our songs about God's power to save, heal, and comfort, gently rose from the church courtyard and into the neighborhood, a sound of freedom, joy, and belonging for all who might come. It was like a free perfume flowing from God's garden into the atmosphere.

Friends, it gave me a beautiful illustration of the believer's faith journey, and its effect on others, your impact on the world around you. 

We may never know who was listening this weekend or how God may have spoken to them. Such is the nature of God working through our ordinary lives. You may never even meet those who catch the fragrance of Christ flowing from the garden of your daily, imperfect walk. But God promises us, 'My word will not return to me empty.' I like to think of it this way: when we breathe out God's truth, and when we live out His word, it's like sending a train carriage into the atmosphere. When that carriage returns to heaven, it won't be empty. It will be filled with testimonies, glory stories, and precious, redeemed souls.

I encourage you to stay strong. Walk in His grace and mercy. Speak into the darkness, and God will move!

⭐ Depression 0 Me 1 ⭐

Somewhere in the warfare
Of doing those 'hard things',
Healing comes like summer rain,
And joy returns like spring.
- Philippa Hanna 

I struggled terribly post-partum and lockdown. If anyone else is struggling I hope this thought encourages you today...

When depression tells you that you can't, you must tell it that you can, or you'll collapse trying! I assure you, nestled within the layers of small daily victories, your healing awaits.

Imagine your journey of recovery like a game of 'pass the parcel'. Within each layer unwrapped, there's another little piece of yourself. There's a piece of you in making a meal. There's a piece of you in daring to do what you love. In meeting with a friend, even in getting dressed and washing your hair, there's a piece of you in getting back to work.

Depression doesn't lift all at once like a headache or pass like nausea. In my experience, it very slowly begins to thin, like condensation on a bathroom mirror, until eventually, you can see your reflection again.

So if today is hard for you, do something small. Wash your hair. Reorganize the spice cabinet. Write a poem. And with every layer, chalk up the score: Depression 0, Me 1.

Sometimes I think intimacy with Jesus is overcomplicated by our worship traditions. Don't get me wrong, I'm a worship leader so I LOVE a good song, a powerful chorus, a well directed ministry moment. But what I really crave is to simply walk with Jesus. To sit by his feet next to an open fire and hear his voice. I really crave to rest my head on his shoulder, to laugh and cry with him and know I'm loved. 

When I was 8 years old I used to play in the woods near our house for hours. I used to walk up to the farm across from my mum's house and run through the fields... Praying aloud. I didn't know what I was doing at the time (chuntering away to myself), but I spoke out all my secrets and problems into the air. I always felt safe, heard and loved. I felt lighter when I came home. Now, I believe Jesus was walking with me. Throwing stones into puddles with me. Finding abandoned rope swings and singing with me. Building dens and writing stories. I believe Jesus was always with me. And I believe He is this close to all who call on him for company. For confidence. For deep, deep friendship. 

Let's never let our ideas of Church get in the way of deep intimacy with the living God who knows us so deeply. We don't need a ticket. We don't need a reserved seat. We just need to call on His name 😭 

Thank you Jesus for loving me. I pray my children will know you like this. I pray my friends will know you like this. I pray all who feel lonely today will know you like this.

As you close your eyes, take a deep breath and give yourself full permission to let go of all the pieces of your life...

let go of your work
Let go of your responsibilities
Let go of your stuff
Let go of people's opinions
Hand your family back to God
Hand the world back to God 
Let go of social media 
Let go of conflict
Let go of accomplishments 
Let go of all the words you heard and said today.
Receive forgiveness, and hand it over. 

All that's truly real in this moment is you and God. And in this space you're no more than a tired baby in His embrace. He's taking care of things. During sleep you have complete permission to disconnect from all the demands life places on you. You can let go of everything you are to others and all perceptions of you. You, on Earth is a story you're living in for a whisper of time. Sleep is your escape from that story for a few blissful hours.

From now until morning it's you and Jesus, in peace and rest. Tomorrow you can pick up life's assignments again with a fresh helping of God's grace and mercy. For now. Let. Them. Go.

Christmas can be all sorts of emotional. It can be such a bright, jolly and exciting time but can also raise feelings of loneliness and anxiety. 😞 Lots of us battle with grief this time of year, and often wish our family situations were more stable, or less complex. Financial challenges also cause anxiety, and if we're not careful we succumb to the pressure of wanting everything to be 'perfect'. 

This year and as the years go on, I'm trying to create new traditions that we can look forward to, and an expectation of joy in our home. For Ozma I don't want Christmas to be about excess. I want it to be about spending time together and doing things together. Whether simple walks, or gift wrap making, (our gingerbread house wouldn't stick together, so it was a deconstructed one, which tasted just as good). Small, thoughtful gifts and taking in the season. 

Simple pleasures, and thanking God for the hope we have in Jesus. MERRY CHRISTMAS 🎄🎁🎄🎁🎄🎁🎄
